</head>
<body>
  <svg aria-hidden="true" style="position:absolute;width:0;height:0"><filter id="grain"><feTurbulence type="fractalNoise" baseFrequency="0.65" numOctaves="3" stitchTiles="stitch"/><feColorMatrix type="saturate" values="0"/></filter></svg>

  <main class="projects-page-main" role="main" aria-label="Projects content">
    <section class="projects-section" id="projects">
      <nav class="projects-topnav" aria-label="Site navigation">
        <a class="projects-topnav-home" href="/">Alan Bagel</a>
        <span class="projects-topnav-sep">/</span>
        <span class="projects-topnav-current">Projects</span>
        <span class="projects-topnav-sep">/</span>
        <a class="projects-topnav-link" href="/blog">Blog</a>
      </nav>

      <p class="section-label">Projects</p>

      <div class="projects-list">

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">01 / Featured</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">Microcosm</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                A 2D roguelike built with Pygame and OpenGL where each run escalates through
                denser enemy waves, tighter resource windows, and sharper decision-making. I
                designed the combat loop around responsive controls, readable telegraphs, and
                clear hit feedback so difficulty feels demanding but fair. Under the hood, I
                focused heavily on performance, keeping frame pacing stable during high-entity
                fights through aggressive update filtering and optimized collision checks.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Procedural encounters and adaptive enemy AI with scaling based on progression, run duration, and player performance.</li>
                <li>Frame-precise combat systems including invulnerability windows, telegraphed attacks, and tight collision handling.</li>
                <li>Math-heavy optimization work using vectorized movement, aggressive state pruning, and low-overhead collision filtering.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">Python</span>
                  <span class="tag">Pygame</span>
                  <span class="tag">OpenGL</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">2D Roguelike</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://alandabagel.itch.io/microcosm" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero">
            <img src="/images/acsl-academy.png" alt="ACSL Academy learn page showing lesson cards organized by contest" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">02</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">ACSL Academy</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                A full-stack ACSL training platform built with SvelteKit, Tailwind, and Supabase,
                deployed on Vercel for fast, reliable access. The platform is structured to
                support long-term skill growth with guided lessons, contest-style practice, and
                immediate feedback loops.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>30+ structured lessons across core ACSL programming and CS topics with progressive difficulty pacing.</li>
                <li>Dedicated practice problem banks and timed contest-style sets for realistic competition prep.</li>
                <li>Account-based progress tracking, quiz workflows, and data-backed refinement of training content.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">SvelteKit</span>
                  <span class="tag">Tailwind</span>
                  <span class="tag">Supabase</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Full-Stack Platform</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://acsl-academy.vercel.app" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">03</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">tiscord</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                A terminal Discord client in Rust for browsing servers, channels, and DMs
                entirely from the command line. I built it around Ratatui for the TUI layer
                and a direct Discord gateway integration for real-time updates. The client
                supports message threading, reactions, search, typing indicators, and inline
                image previews via the Kitty terminal graphics protocol. Tokens are stored
                securely through the OS keychain.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Real-time Discord gateway connection with message streaming, presence updates, and typing indicators.</li>
                <li>Inline image rendering using the Kitty terminal graphics protocol for media-rich conversations.</li>
                <li>Modular architecture across ~12,600 lines of Rust with clean separation between Discord API, TUI rendering, and token management.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">Rust</span>
                  <span class="tag">Ratatui</span>
                  <span class="tag">Crossterm</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Terminal Application</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://github.com/TheSecondComing123/tiscord" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">04</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">algo</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                A custom DSL compiler that translates Python-like syntax into optimized
                C++17 for competitive programming. The full pipeline runs from lexer through
                parser, semantic analysis, optimizer, and codegen. The codegen is modular,
                only emitting the stdlib functions actually used, so the output stays clean
                and submission-ready.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Full compiler pipeline: lexer, parser, semantic analysis, optimizer, and C++17 code generation in Scala 3.</li>
                <li>Built-in data structures and algorithms including graphs (BFS, Dijkstra, Floyd, MST), segment trees, BIT, and DSU.</li>
                <li>Comprehensive test suite validating expected C++ output with end-to-end compilation checks.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">Scala 3</span>
                  <span class="tag">C++17</span>
                  <span class="tag">SBT</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Compiler</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://github.com/TheSecondComing123/algo" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">05</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">Territory War</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                A 1v1 turn-based territory control game where both players move simultaneously
                on a shared grid. I designed the AI progression to ramp from reactive to
                anticipatory strategies, with a loadout system that guarantees at least three
                viable combinations per level so the player always has meaningful choices.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Simultaneous turn-based gameplay with grid enclosure mechanics and territory capture rules.</li>
                <li>6+ AI strategies (Greedy Expand, Wall, Encircle, Deny, Efficient Fill, Corner Trap) with cooldowns and switching.</li>
                <li>Progressive difficulty with strategy unlocks, level restrictions, and a loadout guarantee system.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">TypeScript</span>
                  <span class="tag">esbuild</span>
                  <span class="tag">Vitest</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Strategy Game</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">In Progress</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://github.com/TheSecondComing123/Territory-War" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">06</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">CalcGD</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                Geometry Dash ported to the TI-84 Plus CE calculator in C. Working within
                the extreme constraints of calculator hardware meant rethinking rendering,
                input handling, and level storage from scratch. The port includes jump and
                fly mechanics, a level editor, and practice mode with checkpoints.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Full gameplay loop ported to calculator hardware with jump, fly, and practice mode mechanics.</li>
                <li>Level creation and editing system with custom level file format (8xv).</li>
                <li>Built against the CE C/C++ Toolchain, targeting extremely limited memory and display constraints.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">C</span>
                  <span class="tag">CE Toolchain</span>
                  <span class="tag">Make</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Calculator Port</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">Released</p>
              </div>
              <a href="https://github.com/TheSecondComing123/CalcGD" class="project-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">View project &nearr;</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="case-card">
          <div class="case-hero"></div>
          <div class="case-body">
            <div class="case-content">
              <p class="case-num">07</p>
              <h2 class="case-title">The Legend of Rick</h2>
              <p class="case-description">
                A 2D platformer in Godot and GDScript centered on tight movement, readable
                challenge design, and satisfying level flow. I've been tuning jump physics,
                momentum, and recovery timing so controls stay consistent across both precision
                platforming and combat sections.
              </p>
              <ul class="case-highlights">
                <li>Tuned jump arcs, momentum, recovery windows, and collision behavior for consistent control feel.</li>
                <li>Multiple stage archetypes with checkpoint flow, enemy timing systems, and clearer fail-state feedback.</li>
                <li>Active expansion toward boss encounters and tighter pacing across gameplay and humor beats.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="case-meta">
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Stack</p>
                <div class="project-tags">
                  <span class="tag">Godot</span>
                  <span class="tag">GDScript</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Type</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">2D Platformer</p>
              </div>
              <div class="case-meta-group">
                <p class="case-meta-label">Status</p>
                <p class="case-meta-value">In Progress</p>
              </div>
              <span class="project-link muted">Coming soon</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

